data.title: Dionne Warwick: Don't Make Me Over (2021)
data.meta_description: The story of the iconic singer's fascinating six-decade career in both music and Black and LGBTQ activism.

Fine documentarian David Heilbroner (Stonewall Uprising and the tremendous The Newburgh Sting) is sucked into the biodoc universe with co-director Dave Wooley, and the results are serviceable for an icon who deserves the world, Dionne Warwick, so that's enough to get me to watch this decent feature, Don't Make Me Over.

Apparently one of the final films to be produced by CNN Films â€“ the takeover by Discovery had lead to innumerable cuts, including this entire documentary division â€“ thia People's Choice Award for Documentaries at TIFF delivers what you predict it will: a detailed personalâ€¦

I'm a Dionne fan forever. She blazed a trail and then some. I'm an even bigger Bacharach fan but I think he would have had a very different career if he and David didn't find Dionne. If the stories she tells are true then it seems she was a collaborator as well as singer with them which was great to hear about. It's funny how many times she's presented with a song that she really dislikes, gets convinced to try it anyway, makes it her own and it becomes a giant hit.
